{"key":"processedPost-13051230","value":{"id":13051230,"first":13051154,"last":13051377,"when":1281822433,"utime":"08/15/10 12:47 AM","content":"First, that's not a valid method of pasteurization.&nbsp; You want to hydrate the substrate and then heat it to 140F to 160F for an hour, being careful to stay below 160F.<br />Second, don't scoop spawn out with a spoon.&nbsp; Bang the jar against a tire or phone book, etc., to break up the grains.&nbsp; Then, you can pour them out like sand.&nbsp; The spoon cuts some of the grains in half, exposing uncolonized parts to contaminants.<br />Third, 80F is too hot for bulk substrates.&nbsp; The mycelium will heat up at least ten degrees, and 90F is WAY too hot.&nbsp; This is also the reason for your condensation.&nbsp; It's warmer on the inside of the tub than the 80F on the outside.<br />Generally, when a substrate contaminates prior to first flush, it's the spawn at fault.&nbsp; I suspect the biggest culprit is using the spoon, sterilized or not.<br />RR","title":"Re: lipstick mold problem. could use expert advice."}}